snippet.textDisplay: I’m not convinced of the murder theory. 1. Causing damage to someone’s ribs usually isn’t enough to incapacitate someone, much less kill them. 2. If someone caused damage to the ribs in an effort to hurt her or incapacitate her, you’d think she’d have even more evidence of that kind of injury. 3. You can get broken/cracked ribs by other means (coughing, etc). Who’s to say she didn’t already have a preexisting injury or condition?

snippet.textDisplay: A deep red, flushed skin color (often called cherry red) is the one telltale indicator of carbon monoxide poisoning. It comes from high levels of carboxyhemoglobin in the blood. Unfortunately, it is often a postmortem examination that reveals such a bright red coloring.
